Description: Further Media is an innovative, resourceful media design company, providing highly personalized customer service
Headquarters Regions: Greater New York Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: Further Media is an innovative media design and production company founded in 1993 on the principle of using what was at that time revolutionary new desktop technology. The strategy was then, and continues to be, to maintain a more creative and responsive production environment, dedicated first to customer service and quality consciousness. Further Media caters to a variety of corporate and mass-market clients, including high tech, pharmaceutical, and publishing. Their primary focus, however continues to be the innovative communications work they've done for the food distribution industry. In 1997, in partnership with Al McClain, Further Media founded IdeaBeat.com, a ground-breaking online community for the food retailing industry. IdeaBeat featured daily news, analytical feature articles and "Online Profit Guides" -- mini-sites that educated retail operators on the latest trends and dynamics in particular consumer package goods categories. Sponsors of IdeaBeat included: Coca-Cola, Kimberly-Clark, Kodak, Anheuser-Busch, Minute Maid, M&M/Mars, ACNielsen and many other notable blue chip suppliers to the food industry. Then in February of 2002, these same partners embarked on the path towards the next evolution in trade communications with the creation and launch of RetailWire. RetailWire is a premium online service providing daily analysis and perspectives on current retail industry news - the best source available for staying current and maximizing profits within key retail business areas.  The basic RetailWire service is free to all registered users. It is supported through sponsorships and alliances with leading industry suppliers and vendors.  Further Media principals Rick Moss and Santi Briglia continue to take a hands-on approach to projects, drawing on over 20 years of individual media design experience, ranging from trade promotion and corporate training to network TV graphics and online publishing.
Industry Groups: Advertising, Design, Internet Services, Media and Entertainment, Sales and Marketing

Description: Deep Shift Labs is a technology company focused on web applications development testing.
Headquarters Regions: Washington DC Metro Area, East Coast, Southern US
Full Description: Deep Shift Labs is a small web applications development company that was founded in Sydney, Australia. We are team of four people residing in all four hemispheres across three continents. Our distributed office approach enables our company to provide 24 hours a day service and support for any customer, anywhere in the world. Primarily we develop complex and custom web applications and services using PHP and JavaScript technologies on both UNIX and Windows platforms. Deep Shift Labs started life in 2002 to develop and deliver a web services project for Amity Group (now Bupa Care Services Australia). The applications associated with the initial project have been in production since then, and have successfully evolved with the growing needs of a growing company. After eight years, and iterative project stages, the project continues today with the active codebase now exceeding over 800k lines of code. We are deliberately moving from a professional services type of business to a product based one. Starting in mid 2008 we have been working on our fisrt product - Nerrvana which is bootstrapped. It is available for private beta testing now and was born to satisfy our dreams to run Selenium tests in a cloud. We have also created our second product - Answers, which is the first in Startyco family of downloadable and pluggable web applications for start-ups and small teams. Tired of integration with another SaaS provider? Want to own software, data and have it in the same database to slice and dice? We are on the same page with you. You can easily reach us by email or follow us @deepshiftlabs, @nerrvana, @startyco. We use Twitter as a progress notes tape.

To achieve this, they have created a cooling system that requires no power and has no moving parts.
